<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06086153 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06086153 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  IDAHO; LEGISLATION; RELIGION; GROUP; DRUG; REGULATION  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Legislation legalizing the religious use of the hallucinogenic drug peyote bymembers of the Native American Church won final approval Monday from the IdahoLegislature.;    The Senate voted 35-4 to send the bill to Gov. Cecil Andrus,who has not indicated whether he will sign the measure.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  LEGISLATORS SEND IDAHO GOVERNOR BILL ALLOWINGCHURCH PEYOTE USE  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The bill would make Idaho the 24th state in the nation to legalize thereligious use of the drug, which tribal leaders say has medicinal as well assacramental uses.;    From the beginning of the campaign by Idaho Indianleaders to win approval of the measure, the discussion focused on religiousfreedom.;    The measure would restrict the legal use of peyote toreservations and require those transporting and carrying the drug to haveproper documentation that it is for religious use.;    Tribal leaders estimatethat 1,500 to 2,000 members of the Native American Church are in Idaho.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Boise, Idaho  </CITY><EDITION>  South County  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910326  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  12A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  145  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday March 26, 199100086153,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>